statement.p:
For each of the following linear systems, determine whether
the system is consistent, and, if so, determine whether there
are infinitely many solutions.










	\begin{alignedat}{5}
	2x_1\amp{}-{}\amp x_2\amp {}+{}\amp 3x_3 \amp {}{}
	\amp \amp {}={} \amp 10 \\
	-x_1\amp{}+{}\amp x_2\amp \amp \amp {}+{}
	\amp 3x_4 \amp {}={} \amp 8 \\
	\amp{}{}\amp 2x_2\amp {}+{}\amp 2x_3 \amp {}-{}
	\amp x_4 \amp {}={} \amp -4 \\
	3x_1\amp{}+{}\amp 2x_2\amp {}-{}\amp x_3 \amp {}+{}
	\amp x_4 \amp {}={} \amp 10 \\ \\
	\end{alignedat}








	\begin{alignedat}{5}
	2x_1\amp{}-{}\amp x_2\amp {}+{}\amp 3x_3 \amp {}+{}
	\amp 3x_4 \amp {}={} \amp 8 \\
	-x_1\amp{}+{}\amp x_2\amp \amp \amp {}+{}
	\amp 2x_4 \amp {}={} \amp -1 \\
	\amp{}{}\amp 2x_2\amp {}+{}\amp 2x_3 \amp {}+{}
	\amp 6x_4 \amp {}={} \amp 4 \\
	3x_1\amp{}+{}\amp 2x_2\amp {}-{}\amp x_3 \amp {}-{}
	\amp 3x_4 \amp {}={} \amp 1 \\ \\
	\end{alignedat}








	\begin{alignedat}{5}
	2x_1\amp{}-{}\amp x_2\amp {}+{}\amp 3x_3 \amp {}+{}
	\amp 3x_4 \amp {}={} \amp 8 \\
	-x_1\amp{}+{}\amp x_2\amp \amp \amp {}+{}
	\amp 2x_4 \amp {}={} \amp -1 \\
	\amp{}{}\amp 2x_2\amp {}+{}\amp 2x_3 \amp {}+{}
	\amp 6x_4 \amp {}={} \amp 4 \\
	3x_1\amp{}+{}\amp 2x_2\amp {}-{}\amp x_3 \amp {}-{}
	\amp 3x_4 \amp {}={} \amp 0 \\ \\
	\end{alignedat}

li.p:
Consider the augmented matrices
\begin{array}{ccc} \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right] \amp \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -3 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right] \amp \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.} \end{array}
These examples show that anything is possible: the system may or may not be consistent, and, if it is consistent, there may or may not be a unique solution.

Consider the augmented matrix
\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
We know that every column of the coefficient matrix has a pivot position and that the rightmost column does not. There must be at least as many equations as variables.

This statement is false as illustrated by the matrix

  \left[\begin{array}{rrrr|r}
  1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp -1 \\
  0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1\\
  \end{array}\right]\text{.}

The intersection of two planes is described by a linear system having two equations and three variables. Two possible reduced row echelon forms are
\begin{array}{cc} \left[ \begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp * \amp * \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp * \amp * \\ \end{array} \right] \amp \left[ \begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp * \amp * \amp * \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ \end{array} \right] \end{array}
indicating that the planes either intersect in a line or do not intersect at all. In particular, it is not possible for there to be a single point of intersection.

We have
\left[\begin{array}{rr|r} -1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp -4 \amp k \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 1 \amp -2 \amp -3 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp k+6 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This shows that the system is consistent when k= -6, and the solution can never be unique. If k\neq -6, the system is inconsistent.

We have
\left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 2 \amp 4 \amp 3 \\ -1 \amp k \amp l \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 1 \amp 2 \amp \frac32 \\ 0 \amp 2+k \amp l + \frac32 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
The system is inconsistent if k=-2 and l\neq -\frac32. There are infinitely many solutions if k=-2 and l=-\frac32. There is a unique solution if k\neq -2.

We must have a pivot position in every column of the coefficient matrix so the augmented matrix could look like
\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp * \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp * \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp * \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
Since every column of the coefficient matrix has a pivot position, there must be at least as many rows as columns. This means that there must be at least as many equations as variables.

This leads to the augmented matrix
\left[\begin{array}{rrrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp 4 \amp 8 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp 9 \amp 27 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \frac{17}{3} \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -6 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \frac43 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This gives the coefficients a=2, b=\frac{17}{3}, c=-6, and d=\frac43.

We have the augmented matrix
\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp 4 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp 9 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This system is therefore inconsistent, which means there is no degree 2 polynomial passing through the four points.

The augmented matrix we find is
\left[\begin{array}{rrrrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 3 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp 4 \amp 8 \amp 16 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp 9 \amp 27 \amp 81 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrrrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 6 \amp \frac{17}{3} \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -11 \amp -6 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 6 \amp \frac43 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This shows that there are infinitely many polynomials whose degree is four and that pass through the four points.
